<div class="slide"><h4>FullerScreen 2.2</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <ul>
      <li class="nostep"><strong>F11 to switch to full screen mode</strong></li>
      <li class="nostep"><strong>Use spacebar, arrows, page up/down keys to move to next slide or step</strong></li>
      <li>FullerScreen 2.2 has a slideshow mode</li>
      <li>automatically triggered when slideshow information is present in the document</li>
      <li>no extra JS needed</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Navigation between slides</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <ul>
      <li>spacebar, arrows, page up/down keys to move between slides/steps</li>
      <li class="new">top and end keys to move to first/last slide</li>
      <li class="new">move your mouse pointer to the bottom-right of the screen to show the joystick</li>
      <li>slide manager with thumbnails</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>


<div class="slide"><h4>How it works</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <ul>
      <li>It's an extension to Firefox, the F11 key is your friend to turn it on</li>
      <li>uses only three extra META elements in the document</li>
      <li>uses CSS styles for the 'projection' media type</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Slides</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <p>To describe slides :</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Insert a new META element in the HEAD of your document</li>
      <li>Make it have a <code>name="slideselector"</code> attribute</li>
      <li>Make the <code>content</code> attribute contain a CSS selector matching all slide elements</li>
    </ul>
   <p>For instance: <code>&lt;meta name="slideselector" content="div.slide" /&gt;</code></p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Slide title</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <p>To describe the title of a slide:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Insert a new META element in the HEAD of your document</li>
      <li>Make it have a <code>name="titleselector"</code> attribute</li>
      <li>Make the <code>content</code> attribute contain a CSS selector matching the title of the slide in the context of a slide</li>
      <li>The title will be the aggregation of all text nodes in the element carrying the title</li>
    </ul>
   <p>For instance: <code>&lt;meta name="titleselector" content="h4" /&gt;</code></p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Steps</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <p>It's possible to define steps in slides:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Insert a new META element in the HEAD of your document</li>
      <li>Make it have a <code>name="stepselector"</code> attribute</li>
      <li>Make the <code>content</code> attribute contain a CSS selector matching the steps in the context of a slide</li>
      <li>Navigation in a given slide will, if there are steps matching the selector in that slide, go from step to step.</li>
    </ul>
   <p>For instance: <code>&lt;meta name="stepselector" content="li.step" /&gt;</code></p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Projection styles</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <p>Use 'projection' styles that will be enabled only in FullerScreen mode:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Create CSS style rules inside an @media rule</li>
    </ul>
   <pre>    @media projection {
      body { background-color: red;
      }
      div.slide {
        position: fixed;
        left: 5cm;
        right: 2cm;
        top: 1cm;
        bottom: 1cm;
        background: #d0d0d0;
      }</pre>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="slide"><h4>Highlight the current step</h4>
  <div class="slidecontent">
    <p>How to highlight the current step ?</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Have a style rule in your projection stylesheet for the special class __FSstep</li>
    </ul>
   <p>For instance:</p>
   <pre>  @media projection {
    .__FSstep { color: red; }
  }</pre>
  </div>
</div>

